{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633855"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:57:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:57:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17492"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17492"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0,0.26,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10182"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77875"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10182"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63370"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6661"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23841"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23850"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23862"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26712"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77875"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe left common carotid artery is a major vessel supplying blood to the head and neck.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the origin of this artery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arises directly from the arch of the aorta","Arises from the internal thoracic artery","Branches from the brachiocephalic trunk","Branches from the vertebral artery","Originates from the subclavian artery"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft common carotid artery arises directly from the arch of the aorta \u003C/strong\u003E(Image) as the second branch, after the brachiocephalic trunk. This differs from the right common carotid artery, which arises from the brachiocephalic trunk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the brachiocephalic trunk\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the origin of the right common carotid artery, not the left\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the vertebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The vertebral arteries arise from the subclavian arteries and supply the brain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOriginates from the subclavian artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The subclavian arteries supply the upper limbs and do not give rise to carotid arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArises from the internal thoracic artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The internal thoracic artery is a branch of the subclavian artery and supplies the chest wall\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter its origin from the aortic arch, the left common carotid artery ascends through the superior mediastinum and neck before bifurcating into internal and external carotid arteries at approximately the level of the fourth cervical vertebra.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The left common carotid artery typically arises directly from the arch of the aorta as its second branch.","The left common carotid artery ascends in the neck and divides into internal and external carotid arteries at the level of the fourth cervical vertebra.","The left common carotid artery has both thoracic and cervical parts, unlike the right common carotid artery which is entirely cervical."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Drake RL (Richard L, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM. Gray\u2019s Anatomy for Students. Fifth edition. Elsevier; 2023.","\u201cBranches of the Aorta\u201d by Henry Vandyke Carter is under\u00a0Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gray506.svg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63370"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17492"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21331"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21331"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eBgQUqf4YX71Ah7XVp5UXa9tIeTNWt.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eBgQUqf4YX71Ah7XVp5UXa9tIeTNWt.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":791}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63370"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:15:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:16:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10182"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77875"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":nu